        <!-- comment -->
        <div id="comment_66845865" class="comment_item blogger_comment" style="margin-left: 50px;">
			            <div class="comment_top">
                            
                <div class="comment_top_inner">
                    
                                            <a class="author_photo" href="/social/hp_blogger_Meathead Goldwyn?action=comments"><img class="unloaded-image" alt="photo" src="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/contributors/craig-goldwyn/headshot.jpg"/></a>
                    
                    <div class="author_name has_title">
                                                    <div class="arial_11 bold black">HUFFPOST BLOGGER</div>
                                                <a class="arial_14 bold vertical_color" href="/social/hp_blogger_Meathead Goldwyn?action=comments">Meathead Goldwyn</a>
                        &nbsp;
                        <span class="comment_time">
                            12:30 PM on 11/09/2010                        </span>
                    </div>

                    <div class="author_fans">
                        <a class="author_fans_count" href="/social/hp_blogger_Meathead Goldwyn">88 Fans</a>

                        
                        
                        <div class="clear"></div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="clear"></div>
                    
                                    </div>
                
                <div class="clear"></div>
            </div>

            <div class="comment_body">
                                                                                                                
                I have not tried it this way, but I am skeptical. Here's the problem. The breasts are the thickest part. The center of the breast needs to get to the target temp. It heats by conduction<wbr/>&shy;. The muscle fibers, which are mostly liquid, pass the heat from the surface inward like a bucket brigade. As the exterior heats, the heat is conducted inward. But the speed of conduction is slowed by resistance from the liquid and protein and fat etc. If you cook low and slow, by the time the center hits the target temp, the exterior is not overcooked<wbr/>&shy;. But if you cook hot, the outer layers can overcook. I recommend 325 because the Maillard reaction, that causes browning of amino acids and amps up flavors, starts at about 310F.<br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.amazingribs.com/tips_and_technique/thermodynamics_of_cooking.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www<wbr/>&shy;.amazingri<wbr/>&shy;bs.com/tip<wbr/>&shy;s_and_tech<wbr/>&shy;nique/ther<wbr/>&shy;modynamics<wbr/>&shy;_of_cookin<wbr/>&shy;g.html</a>            </div>
            
            <div class="comment_bottom">
                <div class="comment_buttons">
                	                    
                                                            <div class="comment_links_section">
                    	                        <div id="comment_share_66845865_data_title" class="hidden">hp_blogger_Meathead Goldwyn: I have not tried it this way, but I am</div>
                        <div id="comment_share_66845865_data_link" class="hidden">http://www.huffingtonpost.com/social/hp_blogger_Meathead Goldwyn/smoked-thanksgiving-turkey-recipe-technique_b_778299_66845865.html</div>

						
                                                <a class="comment_permalink" href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/social/hp_blogger_Meathead Goldwyn/smoked-thanksgiving-turkey-recipe-technique_b_778299_66845865.html">
                            Permalink
                        </a>
                                                &nbsp;|                        <a id="comment_share_66845865" class="share_comment_popup_trigger comment_share_link" href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/social/hp_blogger_Meathead Goldwyn/smoked-thanksgiving-turkey-recipe-technique_b_778299_66845865.html">
                            Share it
                        </a>
                                            </div>
