        <!-- comment -->
        <div id="comment_66667802" class="comment_item blogger_comment" style="margin-left: 50px;">
			            <div class="comment_top">
                            
                <div class="comment_top_inner">
                    
                                            <a class="author_photo" href="/social/hp_blogger_Meathead Goldwyn?action=comments"><img class="unloaded-image" alt="photo" src="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/contributors/craig-goldwyn/headshot.jpg"/></a>
                    
                    <div class="author_name has_title">
                                                    <div class="arial_11 bold black">HUFFPOST BLOGGER</div>
                                                <a class="arial_14 bold vertical_color" href="/social/hp_blogger_Meathead Goldwyn?action=comments">Meathead Goldwyn</a>
                        &nbsp;
                        <span class="comment_time">
                            10:42 PM on 11/07/2010                        </span>
                    </div>

                    <div class="author_fans">
                        <a class="author_fans_count" href="/social/hp_blogger_Meathead Goldwyn">88 Fans</a>

                        
                        
                        <div class="clear"></div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="clear"></div>
                    
                                    </div>
                
                <div class="clear"></div>
            </div>

            <div class="comment_body">
                                                                                                                
                Brines are usually not sweet although a few, like this one, have some sugar. But the concept behind a brine is that the salt works cleverly to pull moisture through cell walls into the muscle fibers. Here's an article that describes how brines work their magic:<br />
<a href="http://amazingribs.com/recipes/rubs_pastes_marinades_and_brines/zen_of_brines.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://ama<wbr/>&shy;zingribs.c<wbr/>&shy;om/recipes<wbr/>&shy;/rubs_past<wbr/>&shy;es_marinad<wbr/>&shy;es_and_bri<wbr/>&shy;nes/zen_of<wbr/>&shy;_brines.ht<wbr/>&shy;ml</a><br />
<br />
You can omit the sugar if you wish. Another option is to inject the breasts with chicken stock, salt, and melted butter. The idea is to add moisture and flavor to help prevent it from drying. But brines work better (read the article).<br />
<br />
Or skip it altogether<wbr/>&shy;. The thin gravy in this recipe penetrates the meat very well and moistens it thoroughly<wbr/>&shy;.            </div>
            
